election_record.label: New Hampshire 1819 U.S. House of Representatives

overview.note: The New-Hampshire Gazette (Portsmouth, NH) of March 9, 1819 lists William Plumer, Jr. and George Long together for the final spot on the Republican Congressional ticket, noting that George Long was "Nominated at the Nottingham Convention."

"An attempt, it is already well known, was made from Portsmouth to run Capt. LONG in the place of Mr. PLUMER, jr. Tickets and handbills were circulated, as far as we can learn, in every town of the State; and Capt. L. has in many instances obtained votes where the citizens did not intend to vote for him. For instance, in this town he procured 22 votes under the following circumstances: the ballotting for members to Congress commenced on the brow of the evening - the tickets for Mr. Long were kept carefully concealed until that momen, when they were distributed with great industry by an individual, and 22 were cast for Mr. Long, when probably not more than three persons in the town intended to vote for him; the republicans having previously agreed in convention unanimously to support Mr. Plumer." New-Hampshire Patriot and State Gazette (Concord, NH). March 16, 1819.
